The same way you mentioned:

    String cleaned = s.replace(&quot;&amp;nbsp;&quot;,&quot; &quot;);

It works for me.

[`String.replace(char, char)`][1] takes `char` inputs (or `CharSequence` inputs)

[`String.replaceAll(String, String)`][2] takes `String` inputs and matches by regular expression.

For example:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;String origStr = &quot;bat&quot;;
String newStr = str.replace(&#39;a&#39;, &#39;i&#39;);
// Now:
// origStr = &quot;bat&quot;
// newStr = &quot;bit&quot;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

The key point is that the return value contains the new edited `String`.  The original `String` variable that invokes `replace()`/`replaceAll()` doesn&#39;t have its contents changed.

For example:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;String origStr = &quot;how&amp;amp;nbsp;are&amp;amp;nbsp;you?&quot;;
String newStr = origStr.replaceAll(&quot;&amp;amp;nbsp;&quot;,&quot; &quot;);
String anotherStr = origStr.replaceAll(&quot;&amp;amp;nbsp;&quot;,&quot;&quot;);
// origStr = &quot;how&amp;amp;nbsp;are&amp;amp;nbsp;you?&quot;
// newStr = &quot;how are you?&quot;
// anotherStr = howareyou?&quot;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;


  [1]: http://download.oracle.com/docs/cd/E17476_01/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#replace(char,%20char)
  [2]: http://download.oracle.com/docs/cd/E17476_01/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#replaceAll(java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String)

**You can use [JSoup][1] library:**

    String date = doc.body().getElementsByClass(&quot;Datum&quot;).html().toString().replaceAll(&quot;&amp;nbsp;&quot;,&quot;&quot;).trim();

  [1]: http://jsoup.org/download

